  "prompt": "What is young single slit experiment of diffraction? Explain with diagram.",
  "response": "The **Young's single slit experiment** is a fundamental experiment in wave optics that demonstrates the diffraction of light or other waves as they pass through a single narrow slit. This experiment shows how light waves bend around the edges of the slit and interfere with each other, producing a characteristic pattern of bright and dark fringes on a screen.\n\n### Key Concepts:\n1. **Diffraction**: The bending of light waves around the edges of a slit or obstacle.\n2. **Interference**: The interaction of light waves that results in constructive (bright fringes) or destructive (dark fringes) interference.\n3. **Single Slit**: A narrow opening through which light passes, causing diffraction.\n\n### Setup:\n- A monochromatic light source (e.g., a laser) is used.\n- The light passes through a single narrow slit.\n- A screen is placed at a distance from the slit to observe the diffraction pattern.\n\n### Procedure:\n1. Light from the source passes through the single slit.\n2. The slit acts as a secondary source of waves, which spread out due to diffraction.\n3. These waves interfere with each other, creating a pattern of bright and dark regions on the screen.\n\n### Result:\nThe diffraction pattern consists of:\n- A **central bright fringe** (maximum intensity).\n- **Dark fringes** on either side where destructive interference occurs.\n- **Secondary bright fringes** with decreasing intensity as you move away from the center.\n\n### Mathematical Explanation:\nThe position of the dark fringes is given by:\n\\[\na \\sin \\theta = n \\lambda\n\\]\n- \\(a\\) = width of the slit\n- \\(\\theta\\) = angle of diffraction\n- \\(n\\) = order of the dark fringe (\\(n = 1, 2, 3, ...\\))\n- \\(\\lambda\\) = wavelength of light\n\nFor small angles, \\(\\sin \\theta \\approx \\theta\\), and the position of the dark fringes on the screen is:\n\\[\ny_n = \\frac{n \\lambda L}{a}\n\\]\n- \\(y_n\\) = distance from the central maximum to the \\(n^{th}\\) dark fringe\n- \\(L\\) = distance from the slit to the screen\n\n### Diagram:\nBelow is a simplified diagram of the Young's single slit experiment:\n\n```\nMonochromatic Light Source \u2192 Single Slit \u2192 Diffraction Pattern on Screen\n```\n\n```\nScreen:\n      |          |\n      |   Bright | Dark | Bright | Dark |\n      |          |\n      | Maximum  | Fringe| Fringe | Fringe|\n      |          |\n```",
  "temperature": 1.0,
